         [_t('Newton\'s First Law (Inertia)', 'An object at rest stays at rest, and an object in motion stays in motion at constant velocity, unless acted on by a net external force. Inertia is the resistance to change in motion.', 'Students think objects need a force to keep moving; only a net force changes velocity ‚ÄĒ constant velocity requires zero net force.', 'Identify scenarios where net force is zero and predict constant-velocity (or rest) motion.'),
          _t('Newton\'s Third Law (Action-Reaction)', 'For every force A exerts on B, B exerts an equal and opposite force on A. Action-reaction pairs act on different objects and never cancel each other.', 'Students think third-law pairs cancel; they act on different objects and cannot be combined into net force on one object.', 'Identify Newton\'s third law pairs; explain why they don\'t cancel when finding net force on one object.'),
          _t('Identifying Forces', 'Common forces: gravity (Fg=mg, down), normal (FN, perpendicular to surface), tension (along rope), friction (along surface, opposing relative motion), applied force. All forces require physical contact or a field.', 'Students invent forces like "the force of motion" or "momentum force"; every force must have a physical agent.', 'List and label all real forces on a free-body diagram; identify each force\'s agent.')],
